    "created_at": "2016-02-24T00:26:20Z",
    "updated_at": "2016-02-24T00:26:20Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "If optional and unspecified the default is infinite.\nIdeally it's 'optional but encouraged'.\nIn the future I hope we'll have a mechanism in place to have services\noverride the default, at which time the default flips to encouraging not\noverriding timeouts.\n\nSpecifying via metadata is not supported and will be silently dropped.\n\nOn Tue, Feb 23, 2016, 1:12 PM Nathaniel Manista notifications@github.com\nwrote:\n\n> A few weeks ago when we had the Python idiomaticity review the question of\n> \"why do we require timeouts on every RPC call?\" was raised, and the answer\n> turned out to be \"well historical reasons X and Y but now we don't really\n> care so long as we do what everyone else does\".\n> \n> So let's push for uniformity (as much as possible) among the languages. Is\n> timeout per-RPC optional or required? If optional and not supplied, is a\n> default used? What variance is there among implementations? Is specifying\n> timeout with a metadata value supported? If specified both as an argument\n> and as metadata, which value wins?\n> \n> â€”\n> Reply to this email directly or view it on GitHub\n> https://github.com/grpc/grpc/issues/5378.\n"
  },
